{% extends 'guides/_guide_base.html.twig' %}

{% block guide_header %}
    <h1 class="guide-hero-title">Speed Puzzling Tips: How to Get Faster</h1>

    <p class="guide-hero-lead">
        Speed puzzling technique is learnable. The gap between a casual solver and a competitive one is not talent —
        it is a handful of habits around sorting, searching, and setup, repeated until they are automatic. These are
        the tips that actually move solve times, drawn from how competitive puzzlers in the community work.
    </p>
{% endblock %}

{% block guide_content %}
    {% set d500 = distributions[500] ?? null %}
    {% set d1000 = distributions[1000] ?? null %}

    <h2>1. Sort once, properly</h2>
    <p>
        Most time lost in a puzzle is spent re-searching piles you already searched. Invest the first minutes in one
        deliberate sorting pass: edges out, then group by dominant color or texture. Resist "sorting while building" —
        a half-sorted table means every search costs double. Competitive puzzlers treat sorting as part of the race,
        not a warm-up: flip every piece face-up, make your groups, and only then start assembling.
    </p>

    <h2>2. Do the edge first — usually</h2>
    <p>
        The border is a quick win: edge pieces are easy to identify and the frame gives every later piece a spatial
        anchor. But know when to break the rule. On puzzles with a strong central motif and a bland border (sky,
        gradients, single-color frames), competitive solvers often build the distinctive zones first and leave the
        thankless border for last. The principle underneath: always work the region with the most information.
    </p>

    <h2>3. Build by color block, not by piece</h2>
    <p>
        Searching for one specific piece is the slowest move in puzzling. Instead, pick a color zone — the red roof,
        the yellow flowers — pull every piece that belongs to it, and assemble the block separately. You convert one
        1000-piece problem into many 30-piece problems, and 30-piece problems are fast. Blocks then join into the frame
        as complete islands.
    </p>

    <h2>4. Use trays and keep them shallow</h2>
    <p>
        Sorting trays (or box lids, plates, baking sheets) beat loose piles because you can shuffle a single layer of
        pieces without disturbing the rest of the table. Keep pieces in one layer — a deep pile hides half its
        contents. Trays also make the table portable: rotating a tray to face you is faster than walking around the
        table, and moving the "active" tray next to your building zone shortens every reach.
    </p>

    <h2>5. Light the table like you mean it</h2>
    <p>
        Subtle color differences — sky vs. sea, two shades of green — are where puzzles get slow, and dim or yellow
        light makes near-identical shades literally indistinguishable. Bright, neutral-white, even lighting from above
        removes shadows cast by your own hands and can make an entire difficulty tier of the puzzle simply disappear.
        Of everything on this list, lighting is the cheapest upgrade with the most immediate effect.
    </p>

    <h2>6. Mind your body</h2>
    <p>
        Speed puzzling is an endurance activity in disguise. A table that is slightly too low wrecks your neck and your
        focus within the hour; standing or a high chair with the table near elbow height lets you hover over the whole
        puzzle. Take deliberate micro-breaks on long solves — the stopwatch's pause button exists for a reason. A tired
        brain stops seeing shapes, and you will place more pieces per minute after two minutes away.
    </p>

    <h2>7. Learn the shapes, not just the picture</h2>
    <p>
        On hard sections (skies, water, repeating patterns) the image stops helping and geometry takes over. Learn to
        read piece silhouettes: knob-and-hole combinations, asymmetric shoulders, unusually long or stubby tabs. Many
        competitive puzzlers sort desperate sections purely by shape class and match like a puzzle of outlines. This is
        also where ribbon-cut puzzles (regular grids) reward practice — shape families repeat and become recognizable.
    </p>

    <h2>8. Pick the right puzzles to practice on</h2>
    <p>
        Training on a 2000-piece gradient sky builds frustration, not speed. For deliberate practice choose detailed,
        colorful illustrations around 500 pieces — big enough to exercise sorting strategy, small enough to finish in
        one focused session and try again next week. Repeating the same puzzle is a legitimate training tool: it
        isolates technique from image-reading, and watching your time on a familiar puzzle drop is the cleanest
        measure of improving mechanics.
    </p>

    <h2>9. Time every solve</h2>
    <p>
        You cannot improve what you do not measure. Timing every solve does two things: it makes practice deliberate
        (a clock changes how you search, immediately), and it builds your personal dataset — pace per piece count,
        improvement over months, which images suit you. Use the free
        <a href="{{ path('stopwatch') }}">MySpeedPuzzling stopwatch</a> with pause and resume, and every tracked solve
        automatically feeds <a href="{{ path('puzzle_tracker_app') }}">your personal statistics</a>.
    </p>

    <h2>10. Enter something</h2>
    <p>
        Nothing accelerates improvement like a deadline and a room full of people flipping pieces at the same moment.
        Online races count: same puzzle, same start time, cameras optional. Browse the
        <a href="{{ path('events') }}">events calendar</a> for live and online competitions, or race the
        <a href="{{ path('ladder') }}">leaderboards</a> asynchronously — the puzzle database shows exactly how fast
        everyone else solved the puzzle sitting on your table.
    </p>

    <h2>Know where you stand</h2>

    {% if d500 or d1000 %}
        <div class="guide-callout">
            <p>
                Benchmarks from the community, measured across real tracked solo solves on MySpeedPuzzling:
            </p>
            <ul class="guide-list">
                {% if d500 %}
                    <li>
                        <strong>500 pieces:</strong> median {{ d500.medianSeconds|compactTime }} across
                        {{ d500.solvesCount|number_format }} recorded solves — the fastest quarter finish under
                        {{ d500.p25Seconds|compactTime }}, the top 10% under {{ d500.p10Seconds|compactTime }}.
                    </li>
                {% endif %}
                {% if d1000 %}
                    <li>
                        <strong>1000 pieces:</strong> median {{ d1000.medianSeconds|compactTime }} across
                        {{ d1000.solvesCount|number_format }} recorded solves — fastest quarter under
                        {{ d1000.p25Seconds|compactTime }}, top 10% under {{ d1000.p10Seconds|compactTime }}.
                    </li>
                {% endif %}
            </ul>
        </div>
    {% endif %}

    <p>
        The full breakdown — every piece count, percentiles, first attempts vs. repeats — is in our data guide:
        <a href="{{ path('guide_puzzle_time_by_pieces') }}">How long does a 1000-piece puzzle take?</a>
        Then <a href="{{ path('stopwatch') }}">start the stopwatch</a>, apply tip #1, and find out what your
        baseline is. Everything on this list only works if you know your numbers.
    </p>
{% endblock %}

{% block guide_cta_buttons %}
    <a href="{{ path('stopwatch') }}" class="btn btn-light btn-lg"><i class="ci-time me-2" aria-hidden="true"></i>{{ 'guides.ui.cta_stopwatch'|trans }}</a>
    <a href="{{ path('events') }}" class="btn btn-outline-light btn-lg">{{ 'guides.ui.cta_events'|trans }}</a>
{% endblock %}
